One more perspective, this from Robert Kagan in The Washington Post (https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2022/02/21/ukraine-invasion-putin-goals-what-expect). My cynical side agrees with him: "A final word about Ukraine: It will likely cease to exist as an independent entity. Putin and other Russians have long insisted it is not a nation at all; it is part of Russia. Setting history and sentiment aside, it would be bad strategy for Putin to allow Ukraine to continue to exist as a nation after all the trouble and expense of an invasion. That is a recipe for endless conflict. After Russia installs a government, expect Ukraine’s new Moscow-directed rulers to seek the eventual legal incorporation of Ukraine into Russia, a process already underway in Belarus." A brilliant way for Russia to resolve that pesky Ukraine sovereignty problem.

It is hard to critique NATO and EU leadership. One wonders if even the threat of massive Sanctions will deter Putin. And the argument that NATO expansion in the 1990s is responsible is misguided. Without it Russian troops would be at Poland and Baltic state borders with no Article V obligation to defend All the West and the world can do is grieve for the Ukrainian and Russian peoples, provide all means necessary to aid Ukraine and redouble the NATO and EU efforts to enhance collective security with acts not words. Any negotiation with Putin is futile and we reached again the same point George Kennan made in his famous X telegram. The only way forward is containment of Putin and imposing such massive costs that neither he nor Xi will benefit from naked unprovoked aggression. It is going to be a long and constant struggle In time the West will win Again if leadership and peoples Remain committed to democracy and freedom. That victory is only certain if Western technology continues to match and exceed that of its adversaries.

The problem is that the West i.e.NATO EU constituent nations have predicated sanctions on a bipolar choice invade / not invade. Meanwhile Putin continues to turn up the heat incrementally using the full spectrum of coercive techniques even assassination of Ukraine leadership. Now in totality Putin has blockaded Ukraine by land and by sea and psychologically by raw terror of an imminent invasion. No country no modern nation state can survive this blockade as it extends into weeks. If Ukraine is truly a turning point like Munich in 1938 then US NATO and EU need to take concrete steps to turn up their own asymmetric efforts. Lights out in Minsk and Rostov would demonstrate to Putin that everything other than ground troops like cyber attacks our own sponsored false flag attacks targeted assassinations are on the table. Otherwise Putin wins even if no Invasion. Russian troops remain in Belarus. Breaches of the Minsk cease fire continue. Russia continues it air and naval blockade. Until NATO dispatches a significant force to the Baltic and Black Sea ports and moves significant air forces and further deploys troops in Rumania and Poland Putin will dial up the pressures. A blockade is an act of war. While amplifying force to counter Putin risks World War Iii failure to support and sustain Ukraine will result in defeat without a battle. No good choices here but allowing a de facto blockade of Ukraine is a choice. US and allies continued freedom of navigation exercises in South China Sea and Taiwan Straits are provocative but necessary. Not engaging in freedom of Navigation exercises in Black Sea and Baltic concedes a principle the United States navy has demonstrated since 1797. There can be little doubt that once Ukraine is bent to the will of Putin that Taiwan is next. The rise of ethno nationalism in US and Russia and PRC threatens the whole post WWII order and suggests that by 2024 the US and Russia could both be unequivocal fascist Dictatorships with their own dominant ideology of protecting whites or Russians or the French from cultural if not physical genocide. 2022 is but the opening act and NATO and EU should consider Ukraine and Taiwan existential issues that involve critical security issues. As far as negotiations..yes they will continue but anything other than reciprocal demobilization and removal of Russia blockade of Ukraine is a defeat.

I'm increasingly starting to wonder whether Putin isn't going to just go for Ukraine over the coming weeks and months; I'm wondering whether he might even also go for Lithuania, and potentially even Latvia and Estonia. The USSR ended, but Russia's desire for empire and rivalry with Western European nations started long before the USSR and didn't end after it. Putin himself is a former KGB guy who surrounds himself with other former KGB guys and other people who grew up in the USSR. After the USSR collapsed, Russia had to go through a period of economic and political recovery, but it has regained its strength and ambition. Russia has amassed a fortune from oil and gas and other projects; Russia is the 5th largest economy in Europe and the 11th largest in the world. And it has modernized its military. Putin has dreamed for decades of restoring Russian power. The Cold War may have ended, but it got replaced with a new rivalry with Russia, and Putin seems determined to increase Russian power in Europe. They have laid the groundwork for years: conducting massive disinformation campaigns to weaken the West; building one of the world's top offensive and defensive cyber capabilities; building a very modern military, including modern EW capabilities, anti-satellite capabilities, hypersonic missiles and drones (although they're perhaps a bit behind in UAV capabilities); hanging out around undersea cables all around the world, probably mapping them out and developing plans for cutting them in different war-gaming scenarios; practicing building up the military around Ukraine in preparation for a real invasion (so much so that many seem to be used to the idea of Russian troops around Ukraine, view it as a policy tool, and do not think invasion is likely); and the list goes on and on.

Most Russia/Ukraine experts are concerned especially because of recent Russian troop buildup. However, they admit to not knowing Putin’s mind. Caution would dictate that Putin pulls back, this is not good for his economy. But he may be driven by his nationalistic dreams.

I believe the invasion is coming, most likely within the coming month, and perhaps as early as within the coming week. I believe it's going to happen for several reasons, the exact combination of which only Putin knows. I believe it'll happen because: * Putin wants to rebuild the Russian empire; * Putin is getting older and wants to have a lasting legacy; * Putin thinks the Soviet Union should never have been disbanded; * Putin believes that some or all of Ukraine is rightfully part of Russia; * Putin wants to control a buffer zone between Russia and NATO countries; * Putin is concerned that NATO weapons will increasingly be placed in countries adjacent to Russia; * Putin specifically doesn't want short-range and medium-range missiles in Ukraine (even though he has nuclear weapons and nuclear-capable Iskander missiles in Kaliningrad, and may soon put nuclear missiles in Belarus) and thinks that he must act now or it will soon be too late; * Putin wants a Russian sphere of influence between Russia and NATO countries, and he doesn't want a pro-Western state in Ukraine because he feels it undermines Russia; * Putin doesn't want any former Soviet republic ever again to have a close relationship with NATO (i.e., membership or the placement of NATO weapons or advisors), and so Ukraine will serve as an example of what happens if one gets too close; * Putin feels threatened by having a democracy in Ukraine and doesn't want it to exist as an example; * Putin doesn't want to lose control of Donbas; * Putin thinks the time is right because Europe is dependent on Russian gas, and the US is embroiled in internal controversies; * Putin thinks the time is right because he recently (~18 months ago) got control over Belarus and now has a launching pad for a northern invasion, and he has been practicing and gearing up for an invasion ever since; * Putin wants to weaken European and N American cohesion, both within and between countries; and * Putin thinks his goals in Ukraine are achievable and will incur minimal military costs. I'm sure some of these are more important than others, and I'm sure I've missed some.
